<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading myheaderdiv"><em><strong>How can you estimate=
 the cut angle for a shot?</strong></em></h2>



<p>On <a rel=3D"noreferrer noopener" href=3D"https://drdavebilliards.com/vi=
deos/veps/disc-i/" target=3D"_blank">Vol. I</a> of the <a rel=3D"noreferrer=
 noopener" href=3D"https://drdavebilliards.com/videos/veps/" target=3D"_bla=
nk">Video Encyclopedia of Pool Shots</a>, we show how to <strong>use your h=
and </strong>to recognize 1/4-ball, 1/2-ball, and 3/4-ball hits. We also sh=
ow how to calibrate your hand so you can judge these shots (and the corresp=
onding cut angles) fairly accurately. Knowing these three angles well can h=
elp you estimate the angle required for any shot. =E2=80=9C<a rel=3D"norefe=
rrer noopener" href=3D"https://drdavepoolinfo.com/bd_articles/2014/nov14.pd=
f" target=3D"_blank">HAPS =E2=80=93 Part I: Fractional-Ball Aiming</a>=E2=
=80=9D (BD, November, 2014) also has diagrams and illustrations that help y=
ou visualize and practice standard ball-hit fractions. The cut angles for v=
arious ball-hit fractions can be found at the end of <a rel=3D"noreferrer n=
oopener" href=3D"https://drdavepoolinfo.com/technical_proofs/new/TP_A-23.pd=
f" target=3D"_blank">TP A.23</a>.</p>



<p>A simple way to visualize and estimate cut angles is to imagine an <stro=
ng>analog clock face</strong> (or use one on your wrist). If noon (12) is s=
traight (0=C2=B0), 11 and 1 are at 30=C2=B0 (1/2-ball hit), 10 and 2 are at=
 60=C2=B0 (about an 1/8-ball hit), and each minute is 6=C2=B0. For example,=
 halfway between 12 and 1 ( at 2 1/2 minutes) is 15=C2=B0 (about a 3/4-ball=
 hit), and halfway between 1 and 2 is 45=C2=B0 (about a 1/4-ball hit).</p>



<p>Other methods for visualizing cut angles can be found on the <a href=3D"=
https://drdavepoolinfo.com/faq/aiming/fractional/">fractional-ball aiming</=
a> resource page.  Here=E2=80=99s a diagram from Patrick Johnson illustrati=
ng the where the ball-hit fractions are relative to clock hours:</p>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-large"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"htt=
ps://drdavepoolinfo.com/images/PJ_clockface_ball-hit_fractions.jpg" alt=3D"=
"></figure>
</div>


<p>Below is a <strong>template </strong>from Dan Traylor (from =E2=80=9Cold=
school1478=E2=80=9D in <a href=3D"https://forums.azbilliards.com/showthread=
.php?t=3D281433" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">AZB post</a>=
) that can be useful to estimate cut angles and required aim points when pr=
acticing. Here=E2=80=99s a <a href=3D"https://drdavepoolinfo.com/resource_f=
iles/oldschool_cut-angle_template.pdf" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer =
noopener">printable PDF version</a>. If the center of the cutout is placed =
over the necessary ghost-ball position with the arrow pointed back to the c=
ue ball, sighting to the pocket gives the necessary cut angle, clock positi=
on, ghost-ball overlap, and aim point (center of small circle) relative to =
the object ball. For example, the required aim for a 30=C2=B0 cut (assuming=
 no throw) is through the edge of the object ball. The dashed ghost-balls i=
n the small illustrations are useful to get a sense for the amount of ball =
overlap required on a particular shot.</p>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://drdave=
poolinfo.com/images/oldschool_cut_shot_template_with_GBs.jpg" alt=3D"cut-an=
gle template"></figure>
</div>


<p><a href=3D"https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCPy69FY1TF_b0Fi9Kg33kXw" tar=
get=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">AimPro Billiards</a> has a simil=
ar easy-to-use plastic template and system called <em>AimRight</em> that ca=
n be used to estimate cut angles, ball-hit fractions, and CB directions.</p=
>



<hr class=3D"wp-block-separator has-css-opacity">



<p><strong>from Patrick Johson</strong> (in <a href=3D"https://forums.azbil=
liards.com/showthread.php?t=3D474591" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer n=
oopener" aria-label=3D"AZB post (opens in a new tab)">AZB post</a>):</p>



<blockquote class=3D"wp-block-quote is-layout-flow wp-block-quote-is-layout=
-flow">
<p><strong>1-to-1 slope =3D 45-degree cut =3D 1/4 ball fraction</strong></p=
>
</blockquote>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://drdave=
poolinfo.com/images/PJ_quarter-ball_hit.jpg" alt=3D"1/4-ball hit"></figure>
</div>


<blockquote class=3D"wp-block-quote is-layout-flow wp-block-quote-is-layout=
-flow">
<p><strong>1-to-2 slope =3D ~30=C2=B0 cut =3D ~1/2 ball fraction</strong><b=
r>[Actual: 1.15-to-2 slope =3D 30=C2=B0 cut] </p>
</blockquote>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://drdave=
poolinfo.com/images/PJ_half-ball_hit.jpg" alt=3D"1/2-ball hit"></figure>
</div>


<blockquote class=3D"wp-block-quote is-layout-flow wp-block-quote-is-layout=
-flow">
<p><strong>1-to-4 slope =3D ~15-degree cut =3D ~3/4 ball fraction</strong><=
br>[Actual: 1.07-to-4 slope =3D 15=C2=B0 cut] </p>
</blockquote>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://drdave=
poolinfo.com/images/PJ_three-quarter-ball_hit.jpg" alt=3D"3/4-ball hit"></f=
igure>
</div>


<p><strong>from Patrick Johnson:</strong></p>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-large"><img decoding=3D"async" width=3D"5=
64" height=3D"423" src=3D"https://drdavepoolinfo.com/wp-content/uploads/han=
d_angles.jpg" alt=3D"using your hand to estimate angles and ball-hit fracti=
on" class=3D"wp-image-6482"></figure>
</div>


<p><strong>from Bob Jewett</strong> (in <a href=3D"https://forums.azbilliar=
ds.com/showthread.php?t=3D515850" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noope=
ner">AZB post</a>):</p>



<blockquote class=3D"wp-block-quote is-layout-flow wp-block-quote-is-layout=
-flow">
<p>If you place your tip at the center of the ghost ball and pivot around i=
t from the line to the pocket to the line of the shot (over the cue ball), =
the number of inches the bumper on the cue travels is the number of degrees=
 of the cut angle.</p>



<p>To be precise, you should measure the distance around the arc of the tra=
vel of the bumper, but for cut angles up to 30 degrees the straight-line di=
stance between the two positions of the bumper is pretty close.</p>
</blockquote>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-large"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"htt=
ps://drdavepoolinfo.com/images/Bob_cut_angle_estimation.png" alt=3D""></fig=
ure>
</div>


<blockquote class=3D"wp-block-quote is-layout-flow wp-block-quote-is-layout=
-flow">
<p>The tip of the cue is at the center of the ghost ball. The distance X is=
 the base of an isosceles triangle. If X is measured in quarter inches, it =
gives the angle, pretty nearly.</p>
</blockquote>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://drdave=
poolinfo.com/images/Bob_cut_angle.gif" alt=3D"cut angle estimation"></figur=
e>
</div>


<blockquote class=3D"wp-block-quote is-layout-flow wp-block-quote-is-layout=
-flow">
<p>Here are x (in) x (in/4) actual angle and error:<br><br>1 4 3.82 0.18<br=
>2 8 7.65 0.35<br>3 12 11.48 0.52<br>4 16 15.32 0.68<br>5 20 19.19 0.81<br>=
6 24 23.07 0.93<br>7 28 26.99 1.01<br>8 32 30.93 1.07<br>9 36 34.92 1.08<br=
>10 40 38.94 1.06<br>11 44 43.02 0.98<br>12 48 47.16 0.84<br>13 52 51.36 0.=
64<br>14 56 55.64 0.36<br>15 60 60.00 0.00<br>16 64 64.46 -0.46<br>17 68 69=
.04 -1.04<br>18 72 73.74 -1.74<br>19 76 78.59 -2.59</p>
</blockquote>



<p><strong>from Dead Crab:</strong></p>



<blockquote class=3D"wp-block-quote is-layout-flow wp-block-quote-is-layout=
-flow">
<p>I have a way of estimating cut angles to within a degree. It works for m=
e. Estimating to within 5=C2=B0 would be a cinch.<br><br>1. Place a small p=
iece of tape (blue painter=E2=80=99s tape is good) on your cue shaft 15=E2=
=80=B3 from the tip<br><br>2. Place tip of cue on the CB-OB line so that th=
e 15=E2=80=B3 mark on the cue is over the top of the CB (obviously, not tou=
ching it).<br><br>3. Leaving the tip stationary, swing the butt of the cue =
so that the alignment of the cue long axis is parallel to the line of the O=
B-intended pocket.<br><br>4. Estimate the distance (in inches) from the tap=
e mark on the cue to the CB-OB line (i.e. drop a perpendicular to the CB-OB=
 line from the mark on the cue. Multiply this distance by 4. That is your c=
ut angle, in =C2=B0.<br>  <br>With a little practice, the difference betwee=
n 3.5=E2=80=B3 and 4=E2=80=B3 is obvious, and clearly distinguishes a 14 de=
gree from a 16 degree cut angle. For longer shots, you can use the cue join=
t rather than the 15=E2=80=B3 mark, and multiply by 2 instead of 4 to get t=
he cut angle.</p>



<p>From a practical viewpoint, it is important to note that the tip of the =
cue need not be at the GB center. Since the GB center may be 7=E2=80=B2 awa=
y, a more practical approach is to place the 15=E2=80=B3 mark on your cue o=
ver the CB, with the tip on the estimated CB-GB line (as discussed, for lon=
g shots the CB-OB line is often adequate for longer shots). Then pivot the =
cue around the tip until it lies parallel to the OB-pocket line. Estimate t=
he base of the triangle in inches, multiply by 4, and you are done. For rea=
lly close shots the method can be used by extending the estimated CB-OB lin=
e =E2=80=9Cbehind=E2=80=9D the CB. This saves a lot of reaching. For interm=
ediate and long shots, the 30=E2=80=B3 point of the cue is often easiest to=
 use (just 1=E2=80=B3 above joint), and then the multiplier is 2 instead of=
 4.</p>



<p>If you know the cut angle, you know where to aim from the CB center. 1mm=
 per degree up to 30=C2=B0 and above that, 0.8mm/degree off ball edge over =
30=C2=B0 covers it pretty well. Ball landmarks come in handy. A visible gap=
 becomes apparent between cloth and ball at about 10mm off center (napped),=
 7-8 mm worsted. A 20 degree cut can be aimed at 7:30 or 4:30 on the clock =
face, a 25 degree shot at 8:00 or 4:00. A 23 degree cut is 2mm shy of a 25 =
and 3mm more than a 20.</p>
</blockquote>



<p><strong>from Zafer Barutcuoglu</strong> (via a June 2024 e-mail):</p>



<blockquote class=3D"wp-block-quote is-layout-flow wp-block-quote-is-layout=
-flow">
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a system for using the diamonds to approximate angles amo=
ng the CB, OB, and pocket to determine the required throw-adjusted cut angl=
e and and ball-hit fraction for any shot:</p>



<p class=3D"has-text-align-center"><a href=3D"https://drdavepoolinfo.com/re=
source_files/Aiming_by_Diamonds.pdf" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer no=
opener">Aiming by Diamonds</a></p>
</blockquote>



<p><strong>from Dr. Dave</strong> (related to the document linked above):</=
p>



<p>Here=E2=80=99s a March 2020 <a href=3D"https://youtu.be/4PGSQiq5b9g">vid=
eo demonstration</a> from <a href=3D"https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCPy69=
FY1TF_b0Fi9Kg33kXw" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">AimPro Bi=
lliards</a>, showing how to use the diamonds to accurately estimate the cut=
 angle for a shot.</p>



